      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let's focus on the car issue.\n\nThe high-pitched squealing noise from the front passenger side when braking at low speeds is likely due to worn-out brake pads or warped brake rotors. In most cases, it's a relatively simple fix that can be done yourself with some basic tools.\n\nHowever, if you're not comfortable with DIY repairs or if the noise is accompanied by other symptoms like vibrations or grinding, it's best to have a professional mechanic inspect and diagnose the issue.\n\nIf you decide to tackle the problem yourself, you can start by checking the brake pads and rotors for wear. If they're worn down, you can replace them with new ones. But if the rotors are warped or excessively worn, it's best to have a mechanic replace them for you.\n\nIn any case, it's always a good idea to have a mechanic take a look to ensure the issue is properly diagnosed and fixed. They can also check for any other potential problems that may be causing the noise.\n\nBy the way, have you ever noticed how a well-maintained brake system is like a well-organized goblin lair - everything is in its place, and the goblins can",
